Exploratory Data Analysis

We first explored the structure of the Forest Cover Type dataset before fitting any models.

Feature groups.
The predictors naturally fall into three groups:

  • Continuous topographic and distance variables (10):
    Elevation, Aspect, Slope, Horizontal_Distance_To_Hydrology,
    Vertical_Distance_To_Hydrology, Horizontal_Distance_To_Roadways,
    Horizontal_Distance_To_Fire_Points, Hillshade_9am, Hillshade_Noon, Hillshade_3pm.
  • Wilderness indicators (4 binary): Wilderness_Area1Wilderness_Area4.
  • Soil type indicators (40 binary): Soil_Type1Soil_Type40.

The response variable Cover_Type is a 7-class label indicating the dominant forest cover type (tree species) on each 30m 30m plot.

Basic summaries

Using describe() on the continuous variables, we observe very different numeric scales:

  • Elevation: about 18503850 meters.
  • Slope: 066 degrees.
  • Distance variables: roughly 07000+ meters.
  • Hillshade: bounded between 0 and 254.

In contrast, all Wilderness_Area* and Soil_Type* variables are 0/1 indicators.
This motivates our preprocessing choice: we apply z-score standardization only to the continuous features and keep the binary indicators on their original 0/1 scale.

Class distribution of Cover_Type

The bar chart of Cover_Type shows a clearly imbalanced class distribution:

  • Classes 1 and 2 are dominant.
  • Class 3 is much less frequent.
  • Classes 47 are rare.

Therefore, overall accuracy can be misleading; in later experiments we will also report per-class metrics and macro-averaged scores to properly assess performance on minority classes.

Pairwise relationships

A Seaborn pairplot of three representative continuous features
(Elevation, Slope, Horizontal_Distance_To_Roadways) colored by Cover_Type shows that:

  • Different cover types prefer different ranges of elevation and distance to roadways,
    but their one-dimensional distributions overlap substantially.
  • In the 2D scatter plots, the classes form structured but heavily overlapping clouds, and the apparent class boundaries are curved rather than linear.

This indicates that no single feature can separate the seven classes and that simple linear decision boundaries are unlikely to perform well.

PCA projection

After standardizing the 10 continuous features, we apply PCA and project them onto the first two principal components:

  • In the PC1PC2 plane, the data lie on a curved, U-shaped manifold, reflecting strong correlations among the continuous variables.
  • The seven cover types occupy different regions along this manifold, but still overlap considerably, and there is no obvious linear separator.

This global view further confirms that the underlying decision boundaries are highly non-linear.

Takeaways for modeling

From the EDA we conclude that:

  1. The task is a 7-class classification problem with purely numeric predictors.
  2. Continuous features have very different scales, while wilderness and soil variables are binary; we therefore standardize only the continuous covariates.
  3. Pairplots and PCA reveal overlapping but structured clusters and non-linear class boundaries, which motivates using a flexible non-linear classifier, such as an SVM with an RBF kernel (and tree-based methods) as our main models.
  4. Because of class imbalance, model evaluation should not rely on accuracy alone; we will also inspect confusion matrices and macro-averaged metrics to understand performance on minority classes.

Why SVM?

We choose Support Vector Machines (SVM) because they are margin-based classifiers that work well on medium-sized, high-dimensional tabular data such as the Forest Cover Type dataset. Instead of only minimizing the training error, SVM explicitly maximizes the margin between classes, which tends to improve generalization, especially when some classes are rare. SVMs are also fairly robust to noisy features and can handle multi-class classification via one-vs-rest or one-vs-one schemes, which we use for the 7 cover types.

Why do we scale the features?

Feature scaling is crucial for SVM because the algorithm depends on inner products and distances between observations. In the linear case, the decision function is built from dot products (x_i^\top x_j); with the RBF kernel it explicitly uses the squared Euclidean distance (|x_i - x_j|^2). If the original variables are on very different scales (e.g., elevation in thousands vs. slope in tens), large-scale features would dominate these distances and the SVM would effectively ignore smaller-scale variables. By standardizing all continuous features to have mean 0 and variance 1, we put them on a comparable scale, make the optimization more stable, and ensure that the hyperparameters (C) and (\gamma) have a meaningful and consistent effect on the model.

Why use kernels (especially the RBF kernel)?

The EDA and PCA projection suggest that the relationship between the environmental features and the cover types is highly non-linear; the different classes are heavily intertwined in the original feature space. A purely linear SVM would therefore be too rigid and underfit the data. Kernel SVMs address this by implicitly mapping the inputs into a higher-dimensional feature space, where the classes are more likely to be (almost) linearly separable.

In particular, the RBF (Gaussian) kernel [ K(x, x') = \exp(-\gamma |x - x'|^2) ] can model complex, localized decision boundaries and does not require us to manually construct polynomial or interaction features. It is a good default choice for non-linear structure in tabular data.

Interpretation of (C) and (\gamma) in this task

  • (C) (regularization parameter in SVM)
    (C) controls the trade-off between maximizing the margin and penalizing misclassified training points (the slack variables).

    • Large (C): the model puts more weight on classifying the training data correctly, allowing a smaller margin and fitting more complex boundaries lower bias but higher risk of overfitting.
    • Small (C): the model allows more training errors in exchange for a wider margin and smoother boundary higher bias but better regularization and robustness.

  • (\gamma) (RBF kernel width)
    (\gamma) controls how fast the kernel similarity decays with distance.

    • Large (\gamma): each point only influences a small neighborhood, leading to very wiggly, highly local decision boundaries can fit fine details but easily overfits noise.
    • Small (\gamma): similarity decays slowly, so each point influences a broad region smoother, more global decision boundary that may underfit complex patterns.

In our cover-type classification problem, tuning (C) and (\gamma) allows us to balance underfitting vs. overfitting and to adapt the complexity of the decision surface to the non-linear structure we observed in the EDA.

from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report, confusion_matrix

# Pipeline: scaling on X_train only, then SVM
svm_pipe = Pipeline([
    ("scaler", StandardScaler()),
    ("svm", SVC(kernel="rbf", decision_function_shape="ovr"))
])

# Hyperparameter grid for C and gamma
param_grid = {
    "svm__C": [1, 10, 100],
    "svm__gamma": [0.01, 0.1, 1.0]
}

# Grid search ONLY on the training set
grid = GridSearchCV(
    estimator=svm_pipe,
    param_grid=param_grid,
    cv=3,
    scoring="accuracy",
    n_jobs=-1,
    verbose=1
)


grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("Best parameters:", grid.best_params_)
print("Best CV accuracy on training set:", grid.best_score_)


best_model = grid.best_estimator_
y_pred = best_model.predict(X_test)

print("\nTest accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("\nClassification report on test set:")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

print("\nConfusion matrix (rows: true, cols: predicted):")
print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))

SVM model: results summary

We trained a multi-class SVM with an RBF kernel on the sampled Cover_Type data
(80,000 training samples, 20,000 test samples, stratified by class).

  • Model & tuning

    • Classifier: SVC(kernel="rbf") inside a Pipeline with StandardScaler.
    • Hyperparameters tuned with 3-fold cross-validation on the training set.
    • Best parameters: C = 10, = 1.0.
    • Best CV accuracy on the training set: 0.87.

  • Overall test performance (held-out 20,000 samples)

    • Test accuracy: 0.893.
    • Macro-averaged metrics (all classes weighted equally):
      • Precision 0.85
      • Recall 0.80
      • F1-score 0.83
    • Weighted-averaged metrics (weighted by class frequencies):
      • Precision 0.89
      • Recall 0.89
      • F1-score 0.89

  • Per-class performance

    | Class | Precision | Recall | F1-score | Support | |-------|-----------|--------|----------|---------| | 0 | 0.90 | 0.89 | 0.90 | 7,292 | | 1 | 0.90 | 0.92 | 0.91 | 9,752 | | 2 | 0.87 | 0.85 | 0.86 | 1,231 | | 3 | 0.82 | 0.71 | 0.76 | 714 | | 4 | 0.79 | 0.68 | 0.73 | 327 | | 5 | 0.78 | 0.69 | 0.73 | 598 | | 6 | 0.92 | 0.87 | 0.89 | 706 |

    • The majority classes (0 and 1) achieve the highest F1-scores (around 0.900.91).
    • Medium-sized classes (2 and 6) also perform well, with F1-scores around 0.860.89.
    • Minority classes (3, 4, 5) are clearly more challenging: their recalls drop to about 0.680.71 and F1-scores fall to 0.730.76.

  • Confusion matrix patterns (rows = true, columns = predicted)

    • Most errors occur between the large classes 0 and 1, which are close in feature space, so they are occasionally confused.
    • Minority classes 3, 4, and 5 are often misclassified as neighboring, more frequent classes.
      This is consistent with the high class imbalance observed in the Cover_Type distribution and explains the gap between macro and weighted averages.

Conclusion.
The tuned RBF-SVM achieves strong overall performance (89% test accuracy) and models the majority classes very well, but performance on minority classes is lower due to label imbalance and their more complex decision boundaries. Future work could explore class-weighted SVMs or resampling strategies to further improve recall for the rare cover types.

X_train_bal, _, y_train_bal, _ = train_test_split(
    X_train, y_train,
    train_size=30000,     
    stratify=y_train,
    random_state=42
)

svm_balanced = Pipeline([
    ("scaler", StandardScaler()),
    ("svm", SVC(
        kernel="rbf",
        C=10,            
        gamma=1.0,   
        class_weight="balanced"
    ))
])

svm_balanced.fit(X_train_bal, y_train_bal)
y_pred_bal = svm_balanced.predict(X_test)

print("Balanced SVM (subset train)  Test accuracy:",
      accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_bal))
print("\nBalanced SVM  classification report:")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_bal))

print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_bal))


svm_unbalanced = Pipeline([
    ("scaler", StandardScaler()),
    ("svm", SVC(
        kernel="rbf",
        C=10,
        gamma=1.0,
   
    ))
])

svm_unbalanced.fit(X_train_bal, y_train_bal)
y_pred_unbal = svm_unbalanced.predict(X_test)

print("\n" + "="*60)

print("\nUnbalanced SVM  classification report:")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_unbal))
print("\nUnbalanced SVM  confusion matrix:")
print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_unbal))

Balanced vs. Unbalanced SVM on a 30k Training Subset

To study the effect of class weighting, I trained two RBFkernel SVMs on the same 30,000-sample stratified subset of the training data.
Both models use the hyper-parameters found by the previous grid search (C = 10, gamma = 1.0); the only difference is whether we use class weights.

  • Balanced SVM: class_weight="balanced"
  • Unbalanced SVM: default class_weight=None

Both models are evaluated on the full 20,000-sample test set.

Global performance

Model Test accuracy Macro precision Macro recall Macro F1
Balanced SVM (class_weight="balanced") 0.838 0.78 0.68 0.72
Unbalanced SVM (class_weight=None) 0.838 0.79 0.67 0.72

The overall test accuracy is essentially the same for both models.
However, the balanced SVM has slightly higher macro recall, meaning it recovers minority classes a bit better, while the unbalanced SVM has slightly higher macro precision.

Looking at the per-class metrics, the balanced SVM improves recall for the rare cover types (classes 46) by a few percentage points, at the cost of a very small drop in precision for some majority classes. This is exactly the effect we expect from class_weight="balanced": the loss function gives more weight to minority class errors, nudging the decision boundary to treat them more fairly without changing the overall accuracy very much.

X = df.drop(columns=["Cover_Type"])
y = df["Cover_Type"] - 1

# Stratified sampling: keep 100,000 rows while preserving class distribution
X_sample, _, y_sample, _ = train_test_split(
    X, y,
    train_size=100000,
    stratify=y,
    random_state=42
)

print("Sampled class distribution (normalized):")
print(y_sample.value_counts(normalize=True).round(3))

# Split sampled data into train/test sets (stratified again)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X_sample, y_sample,
    test_size=0.2,
    random_state=42,
    stratify=y_sample
)

print(f"\nTrain set shape: {X_train.shape}, Test set shape: {X_test.shape}")

# Separate continuous and binary features
continuous_cols = [
    col for col in X.columns
    if not col.startswith("Wilderness") and not col.startswith("Soil")
]
binary_cols = [col for col in X.columns if col not in continuous_cols]

# Standardize continuous features (only continuous features need scaling)
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_continuous = scaler.fit_transform(X_train[continuous_cols])
X_test_continuous = scaler.transform(X_test[continuous_cols])

# Combine standardized continuous features with original binary features
X_train_processed = np.hstack([X_train_continuous, X_train[binary_cols].values])
X_test_processed = np.hstack([X_test_continuous, X_test[binary_cols].values])

print(f"Processed train set shape: {X_train_processed.shape}")

# ---------------------- 2. PCA Dimensionality Reduction ----------------------
# Step 1: Analyze variance explanation ratio to select optimal components
pca_full = PCA(random_state=42)
pca_full.fit(X_train_processed)

# Calculate cumulative explained variance ratio
cumulative_var_ratio = np.cumsum(pca_full.explained_variance_ratio_)

# Visualize cumulative variance explanation (for component selection)
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(range(1, len(cumulative_var_ratio) + 1), cumulative_var_ratio, 'b-o', linewidth=2, markersize=6)
plt.axhline(y=0.95, color='r', linestyle='--', linewidth=2, label='95% Variance Explained')
plt.axhline(y=0.90, color='g', linestyle='--', linewidth=2, label='90% Variance Explained')
plt.xlabel('Number of Principal Components', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Cumulative Explained Variance Ratio', fontsize=12)
plt.title('PCA Cumulative Variance Explained', fontsize=14, pad=15)
plt.legend(fontsize=10)
plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Step 2: Select number of components (explain 95% variance by default)
n_components = np.argmax(cumulative_var_ratio >= 0.95) + 1  # +1 for 1-based indexing
print(f"\nNumber of components needed to explain 95% variance: {n_components}")

# Step 3: Apply PCA with selected components
pca = PCA(n_components=n_components, random_state=42)
X_train_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_train_processed)
X_test_pca = pca.transform(X_test_processed)

print(f"PCA-reduced train set shape: {X_train_pca.shape}, Test set shape: {X_test_pca.shape}")
print(f"Variance retained by PCA: {cumulative_var_ratio[n_components-1]:.3f}")

# ---------------------- 3. SVM Classification (with PCA) ----------------------
# Train SVM model on PCA-reduced data
svm_pca_clf = SVC(C=10, kernel='rbf', random_state=42, verbose=1)
svm_pca_clf.fit(X_train_pca, y_train)

# Make predictions
y_pred_svm_pca = svm_pca_clf.predict(X_test_pca)

# ---------------------- 4. Model Evaluation ----------------------
print("\n" + "="*50)
print("SVM+PCA Model Evaluation Results")
print("="*50)

# Calculate key metrics
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_svm_pca)
precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred_svm_pca, average='macro')
recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred_svm_pca, average='macro')

print(f"\nAccuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
print(f"Precision (macro): {precision:.4f}")
print(f"Recall (macro): {recall:.4f}")

# Detailed classification report
print("\nClassification Report:")
print(classification_report(
    y_test, y_pred_svm_pca,
    target_names=[f"Class {i+1}" for i in range(7)]
))

# Confusion matrix visualization
cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_svm_pca)
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.heatmap(
    cm,
    annot=True,
    fmt="d",
    cmap="Blues",
    cbar=True,
    xticklabels=[f"Pred {i+1}" for i in range(7)],
    yticklabels=[f"True {i+1}" for i in range(7)]
)
plt.title("Confusion Matrix - SVM+PCA", fontsize=14, pad=15)
plt.xlabel("Predicted Labels", fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel("True Labels", fontsize=12)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# ---------------------- Optional: Compare with SVM without PCA ----------------------
print("\n" + "="*50)
print("SVM Model (Without PCA) for Comparison")
print("="*50)

# Train SVM on original processed data
svm_original_clf = SVC(C=10, kernel='rbf', random_state=42, verbose=1)
svm_original_clf.fit(X_train_processed, y_train)
y_pred_original = svm_original_clf.predict(X_test_processed)

# Evaluate baseline SVM
print(f"SVM (No PCA) Accuracy: {accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_original):.4f}")
